### Description

Currently, when a listener produces an error during the test execution, it doesn't affect the outcome of the test: the error is reported to the ErrorHandler and it logs it into the console. Here is a relevant part of code:

https://github.com/angular/angular/blob/6d1e6a8bc74e11fe98ca4bd9725dc2c72580b067/packages/core/src/render3/instructions/listener.ts#L228-L240

Here is an example TesBed test:

```
import { Component } from '@angular/core';
import { TestBed } from '@angular/core/testing';

@Component({
  template: `<button (click)="doStuff()">Click</button>`
})
class MyComponent {
  doStuff() {
    throw new Error('doStuff produced this error');
  }
}

describe('MyComponent', () => {
  it('should create the app', () => {
    TestBed.configureTestingModule({declarations: [MyComponent]});
    const fixture = TestBed.createComponent(MyComponent);

    const button = fixture.nativeElement.querySelector('button')!;
    button.click();
    fixture.detectChanges();

    // any valid assertion
    expect(1).toEqual(1);
  });
});
```
Changing this behavior would be breaking, so we can consider adding a TestBed flag to force the test to fail in this case (and generally in any case when an error is reported to the ErrorHandler).

### Description

I'm getting issues implementing ngUpgrade according to the official docs.
I am at the stage when everything works, except navigation from Angular 1 to Angular 13.
It is not clear from the docs where this code should be put:

```
angular.module('rxntBillingApp')
          .factory('$location', downgradeInjectable($locationShim));
```
I tried putting it before `app.bootstrap(el)` in LazyLoaderService, but this results in an error:

> lazy-loader.service.ts:21 Error: Error while instantiating injectable '$locationShim': Not a valid '@angular/upgrade' application. Did you forget to downgrade an Angular module or include it in the AngularJS application?

This is a valid angular upgrade application because when this `$locationShim` downgrade is removed, everything works fine. The reason to introduce location shim is to unify routing, so that AngularJS application can route back to Angular 13 app.

It's not very clear from the docs, but I changed `this.upgrade.bootstrap` inside app.module.ts to bootstrap a regular AppComponent, which then has `<router-outlet>` and routes to Angular 13 test component or to AngularJS component which lazily loads all the static assets and performs the bootstrap.

```ts
// app-routing.module.ts
export const routes: Routes = [
  // Routes rendered by Angular
  { path: 'test-component', component: TestComponent },

  // AngularJS routes
  { path: '**', component: AngularJSComponent },
];

@NgModule({
  imports: [RouterModule.forRoot(routes)],
  exports: [RouterModule]
})
export class AppRoutingModule { }
```

```ts
// angular-js.component.ts
export class AngularJSComponent implements OnInit, OnDestroy {
  constructor(
    private lazyLoader: LazyLoaderService,
    private elRef: ElementRef
  ) {}

  ngOnInit() {
    this.lazyLoader.load(this.elRef.nativeElement);
  }

  ngOnDestroy() {
    this.lazyLoader.destroy();
  }
}
```

And here is the code for `LazyLoaderService`, which is following the official example:

```ts
import { Injectable } from '@angular/core';
import angular from 'angular';
import { downgradeInjectable } from '@angular/upgrade/static';
import { $locationShim } from '@angular/common/upgrade';

@Injectable({
  providedIn: 'root'
})
export class LazyLoaderService {
  private app: angular.auto.IInjectorService | undefined;

  load(el: HTMLElement): void {
    import(/* webpackChunkName: "main.legacy" */ '../../app/index').then(app => {
      try {
        angular.module('rxntBillingApp')
          .factory('$location', downgradeInjectable($locationShim));  // tried adding this code:
        
        this.app = app.bootstrap(el);
      } catch (e) {
        console.error(e);
      }
    });
  }

  destroy() {
    if (this.app) {
      this.app.get('$rootScope').$destroy();
    }
  }
}
```

app.bootstrap code is as follows:

```ts
export function bootstrap(el: HTMLElement) {
  return angular.bootstrap(el, ['rxntBillingApp']);  
}
```

Please advise if you can see anything wrong with the above implementation.

